## Rules and Conventions

- Multiple entities MUST use plural for the field name.
- Single entities MUST use singular for the field name.
- Fields MUST use the camel-cased notation.
  - The first character MUST be lowercase.
  - Connecting words MUST start with an uppercase letter, e.g. “firstSecondThird”
  - Abbreviations MUST stay uppercase, e.g. “ITUser”
- Data MUST be returned below the top level “data” field.
- The entity or entities MUST be specified below the to level “data” field.
  - The entity name MUST be used as a container for the fields, even if it is just a single entity at the moment that is returned.
- API endpoints MUST return only data that clients need (no overfetching).
- Errors MUST have an unique error code per service.
- Error message MUST be expressive and clear:
  - The cause of the error MUST be clearly defined if known.
  - The element of the system causing the error message MUST be clear for the reader.
  - Relevant context, e.g. IDs, entity type(s) and actor(s) MUST be included.
  - If the error message is translatable is a decision made by the service.
  - Any debug related information e.g. a stack trace, must NOT be part of the error response in a production environment.
- Verbs SHOULD be used in resource paths that go beyond the basic CRUD functionality.
Error and failure responses MUST follow the [RFC 9457](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9457.html): Problem Details for HTTP APIs.
- HTTP Verbs:
  - POST MUST be used to create resources.
  - PUT MUST be used to replace a whole resource. E.g. updating 10 out of 10 fields.
  - PATCH MUST be used to modify a resource. E.g. updating 3 out of 10 fields.
- If content is translatable and can be requested in a given language, this MUST be done via the HTTP header Accept-Language.
- HTTP Status Code resolving MUST conform to the HTTP resolve flow.
- Payloads and response bodies MUST be modelled for the needs of the consumers of the APIs, for easy use and consumption. Passing data 1:1 from the DB is not desired except the endpoint(s) are just CRUD or there is a good reason to do so. Naming and structure should always serve the clients needs and not just dump a DB schema to an API client.
- Payloads and response bodies MUST NOT contain more data than necessary.
- ETags MUST be used whenever possible and when they make sense.
- Information that reveals business secrets or poses security risks and GDPR violations MUST NOT be part of the information returned by the API, not in regular responses nor error responses.
- API controllers MUST be free of any business logic.

